## Introduction

The modern web development landscape is dominated by frameworks like React, Vue, and Angular. While these tools are powerful, there's a compelling case for mastering vanilla JavaScript before reaching for a framework. In this post, we'll explore how to build a complete, modern web application using only the browser's built-in APIs.

## Why Vanilla JavaScript?

Before diving into code, let's address the elephant in the room: why would you *not* use a framework in 2026? Here are a few compelling reasons:

- **Performance**: No framework overhead means faster initial load times
- **Learning**: Understanding the fundamentals makes you a better developer regardless of which framework you use
- **Longevity**: The DOM API and Web APIs have been stable for years; your vanilla code won't break when a framework releases a major version
- **Bundle size**: Zero dependencies means zero KB of framework code shipped to your users

## Setting Up Your Project

Let's start with a clean project structure:

```bash
my-app/
├── index.html
├── css/
│   └── style.css
├── js/
│   ├── app.js
│   ├── router.js
│   └── components/
└── data/
    └── api.js
```

## Creating a Simple Router

One of the first things frameworks give you is routing. Here's how to implement a simple hash-based router:

```javascript
class Router {
  constructor(routes) {
    this.routes = routes;
    this.currentRoute = null;
    window.addEventListener('hashchange', () => this.handleRoute());
    window.addEventListener('load', () => this.handleRoute());
  }

  handleRoute() {
    const hash = window.location.hash.slice(1) || '/';
    const route = this.routes[hash] || this.routes['/404'];
    if (route) {
      this.currentRoute = hash;
      route();
    }
  }

  navigate(path) {
    window.location.hash = path;
  }
}

// Usage
const router = new Router({
  '/': () => renderHome(),
  '/about': () => renderAbout(),
  '/404': () => render404()
});
```

## State Management Without Redux

State management is another area where frameworks shine, but you can implement a simple reactive store yourself:

```javascript
class Store {
  constructor(initialState) {
    this._state = initialState;
    this._listeners = new Set();
  }

  get state() {
    return { ...this._state };
  }

  setState(updates) {
    this._state = { ...this._state, ...updates };
    this._listeners.forEach(listener => listener(this._state));
  }

  subscribe(listener) {
    this._listeners.add(listener);
    return () => this._listeners.delete(listener);
  }
}
```

## The Intersection Observer API

For scroll-based animations, the Intersection Observer API is a game-changer:

```javascript
const observer = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {
  entries.forEach(entry => {
    if (entry.isIntersecting) {
      entry.target.classList.add('animate-in');
      observer.unobserve(entry.target);
    }
  });
}, { threshold: 0.1 });

document.querySelectorAll('.animate-on-scroll').forEach(el => {
  observer.observe(el);
});
```

## Conclusion

Vanilla JavaScript is more capable than ever. With the Fetch API, Intersection Observer, Custom Elements, and ES modules, you have all the tools needed to build modern web applications. The next time you start a project, consider whether you truly need a framework — or if the platform itself is enough.

> "The best framework is the one you don't need." — Unknown

