## What Are CSS Custom Properties?

CSS custom properties, often called CSS variables, allow you to store reusable values in your stylesheet. Unlike preprocessor variables (Sass/Less), CSS custom properties are *live* — they can be changed at runtime via JavaScript and they cascade through the DOM.

```css
:root {
  --color-primary: #3b82f6;
  --color-bg: #0f172a;
  --font-size-base: 1rem;
  --spacing-unit: 8px;
}
```

## The Power of Cascade

What makes custom properties truly special is that they participate in the CSS cascade. You can override them at any scope level:

```css
/* Global default */
:root {
  --card-bg: #1e293b;
}

/* Override for a specific section */
.hero-section {
  --card-bg: #0f172a;
}

/* The card uses whichever is in scope */
.card {
  background: var(--card-bg);
}
```

## Building a Dark/Light Theme System

Here's a complete theming system using custom properties:

```css
:root {
  /* Light theme (default) */
  --bg-primary: #ffffff;
  --bg-secondary: #f8fafc;
  --text-primary: #0f172a;
  --text-secondary: #64748b;
  --border-color: #e2e8f0;
  --accent: #3b82f6;
}

[data-theme="dark"] {
  --bg-primary: #0f172a;
  --bg-secondary: #1e293b;
  --text-primary: #f1f5f9;
  --text-secondary: #94a3b8;
  --border-color: #334155;
  --accent: #60a5fa;
}
```

## Toggling Themes with JavaScript

Switching themes is as simple as toggling a data attribute:

```javascript
function toggleTheme() {
  const root = document.documentElement;
  const currentTheme = root.getAttribute('data-theme');
  const newTheme = currentTheme === 'dark' ? 'light' : 'dark';
  root.setAttribute('data-theme', newTheme);
  localStorage.setItem('theme', newTheme);
}

// Apply saved theme on load
const savedTheme = localStorage.getItem('theme') || 'dark';
document.documentElement.setAttribute('data-theme', savedTheme);
```

## Animation with Custom Properties

Custom properties can be used with CSS transitions and animations:

```css
.button {
  --scale: 1;
  --shadow-size: 0px;
  transform: scale(var(--scale));
  box-shadow: 0 var(--shadow-size) 20px rgba(59, 130, 246, 0.4);
  transition: --scale 200ms, --shadow-size 200ms;
}

.button:hover {
  --scale: 1.05;
  --shadow-size: 8px;
}
```

## Responsive Design with Custom Properties

Combine custom properties with media queries for fluid responsive design:

```css
:root {
  --container-padding: 1rem;
  --font-size-hero: 2.5rem;
  --grid-columns: 1;
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  :root {
    --container-padding: 2rem;
    --font-size-hero: 4rem;
    --grid-columns: 2;
  }
}

@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  :root {
    --container-padding: 4rem;
    --font-size-hero: 5rem;
    --grid-columns: 3;
  }
}
```

## Using calc() with Custom Properties

The `calc()` function and custom properties are a powerful combination:

```css
:root {
  --base-size: 4px;
}

.space-1 { margin: calc(var(--base-size) * 1); }  /* 4px */
.space-2 { margin: calc(var(--base-size) * 2); }  /* 8px */
.space-4 { margin: calc(var(--base-size) * 4); }  /* 16px */
.space-8 { margin: calc(var(--base-size) * 8); }  /* 32px */
```

## Conclusion

CSS custom properties are not just a convenience feature — they fundamentally change how we write CSS. They enable:

- Dynamic theming without JavaScript-in-CSS solutions
- Component-level customization
- Runtime value changes
- Cleaner, more maintainable stylesheets

> Embrace CSS custom properties and your stylesheets will become more maintainable, flexible, and powerful than ever before.

---

Try implementing a theme system in your next project — you won't go back to hardcoded values.

## Accessibility Is for Everyone

When we talk about web accessibility, we often think about users with permanent disabilities. But accessibility benefits everyone:

- Captions help people in noisy environments
- High contrast helps people using screens in sunlight
- Keyboard navigation helps power users
- Clear structure helps people with cognitive load

Designing accessibly is designing *better*.

## The Four Principles of WCAG

The Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) are organized around four principles, often abbreviated as **POUR**:

1. **Perceivable**: Information must be presentable to users in ways they can perceive
2. **Operable**: UI components and navigation must be operable
3. **Understandable**: Information and UI operation must be understandable
4. **Robust**: Content must be robust enough to be interpreted by assistive technologies

## Semantic HTML: The Foundation

The most impactful accessibility improvement is using semantic HTML correctly. Semantics communicate *meaning* to assistive technologies:

```html
<!-- Bad: No semantic meaning -->
<div class="nav">
  <div class="nav-item" onclick="navigate()">Home</div>
</div>

<!-- Good: Semantic meaning -->
<nav aria-label="Main navigation">
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/">Home</a></li>
    <li><a href="/about">About</a></li>
  </ul>
</nav>
```

## ARIA: When HTML Isn't Enough

ARIA (Accessible Rich Internet Applications) attributes add semantic information when HTML alone is insufficient:

```html
<!-- Custom modal dialog -->
<div 
  role="dialog" 
  aria-modal="true"
  aria-labelledby="modal-title"
  aria-describedby="modal-desc"
>
  <h2 id="modal-title">Confirm Action</h2>
  <p id="modal-desc">Are you sure you want to delete this item?</p>
  <button>Cancel</button>
  <button>Delete</button>
</div>

<!-- Live region for dynamic content -->
<div aria-live="polite" aria-atomic="true">
  <!-- Status messages announced to screen readers -->
</div>
```

## Focus Management

Proper focus management is critical for keyboard-only users:

```javascript
class Modal {
  open() {
    this.element.removeAttribute('hidden');
    // Save focus position
    this.previousFocus = document.activeElement;
    // Move focus to modal
    this.element.querySelector('[autofocus]').focus();
    // Trap focus inside modal
    this.trapFocus();
  }

  close() {
    this.element.setAttribute('hidden', '');
    // Restore focus
    this.previousFocus?.focus();
  }

  trapFocus() {
    const focusable = this.element.querySelectorAll(
      'button, [href], input, select, textarea, [tabindex]:not([tabindex="-1"])'
    );
    const firstEl = focusable[0];
    const lastEl = focusable[focusable.length - 1];

    this.element.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
      if (e.key !== 'Tab') return;
      if (e.shiftKey && document.activeElement === firstEl) {
        e.preventDefault();
        lastEl.focus();
      } else if (!e.shiftKey && document.activeElement === lastEl) {
        e.preventDefault();
        firstEl.focus();
      }
    });
  }
}
```

## Color and Contrast

Color contrast ratios must meet WCAG standards:

```css
/* WCAG AA requires 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text */
:root {
  /* These combinations pass WCAG AA */
  --text-on-dark: #f1f5f9;     /* on #0f172a: ~15:1 ratio */
  --text-on-light: #1e293b;   /* on #ffffff: ~16:1 ratio */
  --accent-accessible: #2563eb; /* on white: ~5.9:1 ratio */
}

/* Never use color alone to convey information */
.error-field {
  border-color: #ef4444;
  /* Also include an icon or text label */
}

.error-field::after {
  content: " ⚠ Error";
  color: #ef4444;
}
```

## Reduced Motion

Respect users' motion preferences:

```css
/* Define animations normally */
.animated-element {
  transition: transform 300ms ease, opacity 300ms ease;
}

/* Remove or reduce animations when preferred */
@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
  .animated-element {
    transition: opacity 100ms ease; /* Keep subtle fade, remove movement */
  }

  /* Stop infinite animations completely */
  .spinning-loader {
    animation: none;
  }
}
```

## Testing Accessibility

Use these tools and techniques:

- **axe DevTools**: Browser extension for automated testing
- **NVDA** (Windows) or **VoiceOver** (Mac): Test with actual screen readers
- **Keyboard-only navigation**: Unplug your mouse for a day
- **Color contrast checkers**: WebAIM Contrast Checker
- **Lighthouse accessibility audit**: Built into Chrome DevTools

> "Accessibility is not a feature. It is a social trend." — Antonio Santos

---

Accessibility is a journey, not a destination. Start with semantic HTML, add ARIA where needed, test with keyboard and screen reader, and iterate continuously.
